TypeScript is a statically-typed superset of JavaScript developed by Microsoft. It adds optional type annotations to JavaScript, enabling developers to catch type-related errors during development and compilation, rather than at runtime. TypeScript code is transpiled into plain JavaScript, which can be executed in any JavaScript environment. By providing static typing, TypeScript helps developers write more robust and maintainable code, with better tooling support like autocompletion, refactoring, and type checking.

Duck typing is a programming concept where an object's type is determined by its behavior (i.e., the methods and properties it has) rather than by its class or inheritance hierarchy. In other words, if an object "looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck," then it is considered a duck, regardless of its actual class or implementation. Duck typing is commonly used in dynamic languages like JavaScript, where type information is not available at compile time.

In TypeScript, duck typing is achieved through a feature called "structural typing." Structural typing allows TypeScript to infer the type of an object based on its shape, i.e., the properties and methods it has, rather than its explicit type annotation. This enables TypeScript to work seamlessly with existing JavaScript code and libraries, as it can understand and type-check objects based on their structure, even if they don't have explicit type annotations.

For example, consider the following TypeScript code:

typescript
interface Duck {
  quack(): void;
  swim(): void;
}

function doDuckStuff(duck: Duck) {
  duck.quack();
  duck.swim();
}

const myDuck = {
  quack: () => console.log("Quack!"),
  swim: () => console.log("Swimming..."),
};

doDuckStuff(myDuck); // This works, as myDuck has the same structure as the Duck interface


In this example, the `doDuckStuff` function expects an object of type `Duck`. The `myDuck` object is not explicitly typed as `Duck`, but it has the same structure (i.e., the `quack` and `swim` methods), so TypeScript considers it a valid argument for the `doDuckStuff` function. This is an example of duck typing in TypeScript using structural typing.

Here's a simple C++ function that converts a limited set of Markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text. This function only supports bold, italic, and links. You can extend this function to support more Markdown features if needed.

cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Replace bold text (**text** or __text__)
    std::regex boldPattern(R"((\*\*|__)(.+?)\1)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, boldPattern, "<strong>$2</strong>");

    // Replace italic text (*text* or _text_)
    std::regex italicPattern(R"((\*|_)(.+?)\1)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicPattern, "<em>$2</em>");

    // Replace links ([text](url))
    std::regex linkPattern(R"(\[(.+?)\]\((.+?)\))");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, linkPattern, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "This is **bold** and *italic* text with a [link](https://www.example.com).";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << "Markdown: " << markdown << std::endl;
    std::cout << "HTML: " << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}


